{"id":"1011.3986","submitter":"Reiner Lauterbach","authors":"Reiner Lauterbach, Paul Matthews","title":"Do absolutely irreducible group actions have odd dimensional fixed point\n  spaces?","comments":"38 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In his volume [5] on \"Symmetry Breaking for Compact Lie Groups\" Mike Field\nquotes a private communication by Jorge Ize claiming that any bifurcation\nproblem with absolutely irreducible group action would lead to bifurcation of\nsteady states. The proof should come from the fact that any absolutely\nirreducible representation possesses an odd dimensional fixed point space.\n  In this paper we show that there are many examples of groups which have\nabsolutely irreducible representations but no odd dimensional fixed point\nspace. This observation may be relevant also for some degree theoretic\nconsiderations concerning equivariant bifurcation. Moreover we show that our\nexamples give rise to some interesting Hamiltonian dynamics and we show that\ndespite some complications we can go a long way towards doing explicit\ncomputations and providing complete proofs. For some of the invariant theory\nneeded we will depend on some computer aided computations. The work presented\nhere greatly benefited from the computer algebra program GAP [6], which is an\nindispensable aid for doing the required group theory computations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Nov 2010 16:09:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-11-18"}
