{"id":"1011.4027","submitter":"Tristan Tager","authors":"Annie Carter, Daniel Lithio, Robert Niichel, and Tristan Tager","title":"Beta Spaces: New Generalizations of Typically-Metric Properties","comments":"PREPRINT, submitted to arXiv for NSF review","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GN","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is well-known that point-set topology (without additional structure) lacks\nthe capacity to generalize the analytic concepts of completeness, boundedness,\nand other typically-metric properties. The ability of metric spaces to capture\nthis information is tied to the fact that the topology is generated by open\nballs whose radii can be compared. In this paper, we construct spaces that\ngeneralize this property, called $\\beta$-spaces, and show that they provide a\nframework for natural definitions of the above concepts. We show that\n$\\beta$-spaces are strictly more general than uniform spaces, a common\ngeneralization of metric spaces. We then conclude by proving generalizations of\nseveral typically-metric theorems, culminating in a broader statement of the\nContraction Mapping Theorem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Nov 2010 19:03:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-11-18"}
